That’s right—<strong>five of these programs are specifically for schools</strong>, ensuring kids don’t go hungry. The $1 billion CCC cut doesn’t touch these. So why the hysteria? Let’s dig into what some of these programs actually do.
<h4 class="western">Spotlight on 5 Fully Funded School Programs</h4>
Here’s a closer look at five of the fully funded programs supporting schools, straight from the facts:
<ol>
 	<li><strong>Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Program (FFVP)</strong>
This program provides free fresh fruits and vegetables to elementary school kids during the school day. It’s designed to boost healthy eating habits and fight childhood obesity. Schools in low-income areas get priority, and it’s fully funded to keep kids nourished and learning.</li>
 	<li><strong>National School Lunch Program (NSLP)</strong>
The NSLP serves millions of kids affordable, nutritious lunches every school day. It’s a cornerstone of school nutrition, offering free or reduced-price meals to eligible students. Funding? Intact and rolling strong.</li>
 	<li><strong>School Breakfast Program (SBP)</strong>
Breakfast is the most important meal of the day, and the SBP ensures kids start their mornings right with healthy options. Like the NSLP, it’s fully funded and targets kids who might otherwise skip breakfast, especially in low-income families.</li>
 	<li><strong>Special Milk Program (SMP)</strong>
Got milk? This program does. It provides milk to kids in schools and childcare settings that don’t participate in other federal meal programs. It’s a simple, effective way to get calcium and nutrients to growing bodies—fully funded, no cuts here.</li>
 	<li><strong>Summer Food Service Program (SFSP)</strong>
When school’s out, hunger doesn’t stop. The SFSP keeps kids and teens fed during summer break, serving meals at schools, parks, and community sites. It’s fully funded to bridge the gap for kids who rely on school meals year-round.</li>
</ol>
<h4 class="western">Why the Misinformation?</h4>
The media’s obsession with the CCC cut ignores these thriving programs. The CCC might be a New Deal-era relic, but cutting its $1 billion doesn’t starve kids—it just trims a faceless fund. Meanwhile, these 16 programs are doing the real work. So, news outlets, do your job: report the full story. How many people are profiting off the CCC while kids still get fed through these other channels? Follow the money.
